    <p>I'll be straight with you. I was researching and experimenting with peptides before they were all over social media and every fitness influencer's feed. I'm not going to sit here and tell you they're all hype — that's not the point of this post and frankly it's more complicated than that.</p>

    <p>The point is something I learned the hard way: <strong>it doesn't matter what you're taking if the foundation isn't solid.</strong> I've watched guys drop serious money on the latest thing — peptides, hormone support, advanced recovery stacks — while eating 70 grams of protein a day and skipping the gym half the week. And then wondering why nothing is working.</p>

    <p>The supplement isn't the problem. The sequence is.</p>

    <div class="killer-line">
      Peptides are a multiplier.<br><span>You can't multiply zero.</span>
    </div>

    <h2>The Supplement Industry's Dirty Secret</h2>

    <p>Here's what nobody selling you anything wants to say out loud: every single muscle-building tool — whether it's a peptide, a hormone protocol, creatine, or anything else — works by supporting or amplifying processes that already exist in your body. Specifically, muscle protein synthesis. The repair and rebuilding that happens when you train.</p>

    <p>For that process to work, two things have to be in place:</p>

    <p><strong>1. A training stimulus.</strong> Your muscles need a reason to rebuild bigger and stronger. Resistance training creates micro-damage in muscle fibers. Recovery rebuilds them slightly stronger. No stimulus, no signal. No signal, nothing to amplify.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Adequate protein.</strong> Your muscles are made of protein. When they repair after training, they use dietary amino acids as the raw material. If you're not eating enough protein — specifically enough to clear what researchers call the leucine threshold at each meal — your muscles don't have the building blocks to respond, no matter what else is in the system.</p>

    <p>Everything else — every supplement on the market, including the ones with real research behind them — sits on top of those two things. Remove either one and you've removed the foundation everything else depends on.</p>

