    <h2>The Protein Number That Has to Be There First</h2>

    <p>For men over 40, the research is consistent: you need at least <strong>1.2 grams of protein per kilogram of bodyweight per day</strong> — that's roughly <strong>0.55 grams per pound</strong> — just to preserve muscle mass. That's before any serious recomposition goals. For a 180-pound man, that's around 100 grams minimum.</p>

    <p>Most men eating without tracking are landing at 70–80 grams. That gap — 20 to 30 grams below the minimum preservation threshold — is where muscle is quietly being lost. And no supplement closes a protein gap. That's not what supplements do.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p>After 40, a condition called <strong>anabolic resistance</strong> means your body becomes less efficient at using dietary protein to build and repair muscle. This is actually an argument for <em>more</em> protein — not less — and it makes hitting your daily target even more critical. Any supplement you're considering works through pathways that depend on protein being available. It's not optional.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Want to see what hitting that number actually looks like in real food? The clearest place to start is <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">what 120 grams of protein looks like in a real day</a> — no supplements required, just food most men already eat.</p>

    <h2>I'm Not Telling You Supplements Don't Work</h2>

    <p>That's not what this is. I've been in this space long enough to know that some things have real research behind them and some don't. The supplement industry has both ends of that spectrum and everything in between.</p>

    <p>What I'm telling you is that the guys who get the most out of anything they add to their stack are the ones who have the foundation dialed in first. Training is consistent. Protein is tracked and hitting the target. Sleep is solid. Then — and only then — does adding something on top actually move the needle in a way you can feel and measure.</p>

    <p>The reason most men don't get results from supplements isn't that the supplements don't work. It's that they're trying to optimize the third floor of a building that doesn't have a foundation yet.</p>

    <h2>The Cheapest Performance Enhancement Available</h2>

    <p>Here's the part that always gets me. The single most impactful change most men over 40 can make for muscle preservation and body composition costs almost nothing. It's closing their protein gap.</p>

    <p>Getting from 75 grams to 120 grams of protein per day — with chicken, eggs, Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, ground beef — costs a few dollars more per week in groceries. That's it. No prescription. No research rabbit holes. No waiting for a package to arrive.</p>

    <p>And when that foundation is solid, everything else — including whatever you're researching right now — actually has something to work with.</p>

